{"source":"openstax","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-1/pages/3-4-derivatives-as-rates-of-change","license":"CC-BY-4.0","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 1 (CC-BY 4.0)","fetched_at":"2026-04-20T04:53:21.488Z","kind":"problem","raw_text":"If f(x) = x³ - 6x, find f'(x) and evaluate at x = 2.","metadata":{"id":"openstax-derivatives-basic-0","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-1/pages/3-4-derivatives-as-rates-of-change","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 1 (CC-BY 4.0)","topic":"calculus","concept_id":"derivatives-basic","difficulty":"easy","year":2022,"question_text":"If f(x) = x³ - 6x, find f'(x) and evaluate at x = 2.","correct_answer":"6","explanation":"f'(x) = 3x² - 6; f'(2) = 12 - 6 = 6.","marks":2}}
{"source":"openstax","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-1/pages/5-4-integration-formulas-and-the-net-change-theorem","license":"CC-BY-4.0","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 1 (CC-BY 4.0)","fetched_at":"2026-04-20T04:53:21.489Z","kind":"problem","raw_text":"Evaluate ∫₀² (3x² + 2) dx.","metadata":{"id":"openstax-definite-integrals-1","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-1/pages/5-4-integration-formulas-and-the-net-change-theorem","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 1 (CC-BY 4.0)","topic":"calculus","concept_id":"definite-integrals","difficulty":"easy","year":2022,"question_text":"Evaluate ∫₀² (3x² + 2) dx.","correct_answer":"12","explanation":"[x³ + 2x]₀² = (8 + 4) - 0 = 12.","marks":2}}
{"source":"openstax","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-2/pages/6-3-taylor-and-maclaurin-series","license":"CC-BY-4.0","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 2 (CC-BY 4.0)","fetched_at":"2026-04-20T04:53:21.489Z","kind":"problem","raw_text":"The first three non-zero terms of the Maclaurin series for e^x are:","metadata":{"id":"openstax-taylor-series-2","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-2/pages/6-3-taylor-and-maclaurin-series","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 2 (CC-BY 4.0)","topic":"calculus","concept_id":"taylor-series","difficulty":"medium","year":2022,"question_text":"The first three non-zero terms of the Maclaurin series for e^x are:","correct_answer":"1 + x + x²/2","options":{"A":"1 + x + x²/2","B":"x + x² + x³/6","C":"1 + x² + x⁴/24","D":"x + x²/2 + x³/6"},"explanation":"e^x = Σ x^n/n! → 1 + x + x²/2! + x³/3! + ...","marks":2}}
{"source":"openstax","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/4-3-partial-derivatives","license":"CC-BY-4.0","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 3 (CC-BY 4.0)","fetched_at":"2026-04-20T04:53:21.489Z","kind":"problem","raw_text":"If z = x²y + sin(xy), find ∂z/∂y.","metadata":{"id":"openstax-partial-derivatives-3","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/4-3-partial-derivatives","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 3 (CC-BY 4.0)","topic":"calculus","concept_id":"partial-derivatives","difficulty":"medium","year":2022,"question_text":"If z = x²y + sin(xy), find ∂z/∂y.","correct_answer":"x² + x·cos(xy)","explanation":"∂/∂y of x²y is x². ∂/∂y of sin(xy) is x·cos(xy).","marks":2}}
{"source":"openstax","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-2/pages/5-2-the-divergence-and-integral-tests","license":"CC-BY-4.0","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 2 (CC-BY 4.0)","fetched_at":"2026-04-20T04:53:21.489Z","kind":"problem","raw_text":"Does the series Σ 1/n² converge?","metadata":{"id":"openstax-series-4","source_url":"https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-2/pages/5-2-the-divergence-and-integral-tests","attribution":"OpenStax Calculus Volume 2 (CC-BY 4.0)","topic":"calculus","concept_id":"series","difficulty":"medium","year":2022,"question_text":"Does the series Σ 1/n² converge?","correct_answer":"Yes","options":{"A":"Yes","B":"No","C":"Only conditionally","D":"Unknown"},"explanation":"p-series with p=2 > 1 → converges (value = π²/6).","marks":1}}